metadata.name: Bamboo #112
metadata.description:
During my childhood we had a small patch of bamboo in our backyard. 
I fondly remember playing with the hollow sticks but also cutting myself on the fibrous leaves.
"Bamboo" aims to capture the adventures I would envision while looking at that small jungle in my garden.

Inspiration was drawn from pointillism, botanical illustration and naive art.

The piece is purely generative, in the sense of painting the picture with code via p5js points and shapes, no assets are used.

Generative parameters include density of elements, parameters of elements and color. 

Thank you so much for collecting!

's' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png with border

'b' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png without border

metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #193
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)

metadata.name: Neuro-Daguerreotypes #44
metadata.description:
Landscapes with islands lost in the fog are old neuro-daguerreotypes.
Their surface changes, developing from rocks, fern forests, to cities and metropolises that gradually fall into decay, ruins, turn into slums or shelters of other creatures.
The landscape of the islands includes:
- rocks
- hills
- dwellings of elves
- ruins
- villages by the sea
- ghettos and slums
- metropolises and skyscrapers
When viewed from space, by and large, nothing changes, but in rare cases you will be able to see the whole picture.

Artwork is based on PNG layers (with masks), Disco Diffusion, python and p5.js code.

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.

metadata.name: Waxing Crescent #105
metadata.description:
A generator for the mascot of darkness.

The moons are generated with a real-time GAN of 1.6M parameters that has been trained on thousands of photos collected on the internet.

Each grid performs a unique cycle of 29.53 days, in sync with the iconic celestial body.

Press "r" to render the full cycle as a 2s GIF.

metadata.name: Last Lines #148
metadata.description:
How many lines have been drawn on fxhash since that first generative logo started growing on a Wednesday in early November? How many brush strokes, wires, cables, threads? Many thousands per mint? Millions per project? Billions in total? Shall we add just a few more to celebrate the end of the genesis? Here are 222 iterations with 111 lines each. Each line connects two edges of the canvas but may get deflected by hidden attractors in an attempt to minimize friction and deviation from its path.

Press [p]rint to save a high resolution capture.

This artwork is fully generative and was entirely hand-coded in 4,400 characters of plain JavaScript. Forever limited to 222 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.

metadata.name: Action Fields #69
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: Telar #52
metadata.description:
Telar is a study about weaving.

Weaving is one of the oldest crafts in the world. It's been part of our history for almost 30,000 years. 

We are used as species to continuously see patterns generated by millions of binary decisions between colors. These patterns are part of the social DNA of almost every human culture, and their complex aesthetics generated by the most simple inputs are fascinating to me.

This piece, inspired by the mechanism of the Jacquard Loom — which is widely considered the first computer — uses combinations of colors, series, threading, treadling, and tie-up patterns to generate a unique 360-by-360-thread Telar ("loom" in Spanish). 

The algorithm called telar.js uses the hash to select some colors from preselected patterns and uses the input series to generate a base model with a starting pattern. After that, multiple iterations alter the model appending new tie-ups and modifying the threading or treadling and colors while keeping the design consistent. A resulting matrix containing each intersection then gets drawn on the screen resulting in a high-definition image the viewer can zoom in and see in detail. 

This algorithm takes too many pseudorandom trait values as its inputs that naming them was meaningless, so I would prefer collectors to focus on the subjective aesthetic values of the outputs. Therefore I am hiding the features for this collection.

Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print. Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.
